<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1471,1496]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Remarks.</emphasis>
The female of 
<taxonomicName box="[488,613,1471,1496]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Pattonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gulo" subGenus="Peckia">
<emphasis box="[488,509,1473,1496]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[525,544,1473,1496]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[563,613,1471,1496]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">gulo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shares some morphological similarities with those of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Aldrich" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[1223,1388,1471,1496]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Pattonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hillifera" subGenus="Peckia">
<emphasis box="[1223,1244,1473,1496]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1260,1278,1473,1496]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1298,1388,1471,1496]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">hillifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[151,278,1508,1533]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Pattonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lutzi" subGenus="Peckia">
<emphasis box="[151,172,1509,1532]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[190,209,1509,1532]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[230,278,1508,1533]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">lutzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, such as T5 with a triangular posterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[834,925,1508,1533]" captionStart="FIGURES 75–80" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1907,1930]" captionTargetBox="[176,1416,193,1882]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[168,1416,193,1890]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 75–80. Peckia (Peckia) gulo (Fabricius), female from Pará, Bragança (MPEG). 75. Abdominal sternites and tergites 5 and 6 in ventral view. 76. Epiproct, cercus and hypoproct in apical view. 77. Spermatheca in lateral view. 78. Abdomen in posterior view. 79. Abdomen in dorsal view. 80. Abdomen in ventral view. Scale bars: 73, 76–78 = 2 mm; 74–75 = 0.5 mm. Abbreviations: CE = cercus; EP = epiproct; HP = hypoproct; ST = sternite; T = tergite." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1456145/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Figs 78</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[939,969,1508,1532]" captionStart="FIGURES 81–86" captionStartId="24.[151,264,1911,1934]" captionTargetBox="[176,1406,197,1883]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[173,1406,193,1888]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 81–86. Peckia (Peckia) hillifera (Aldrich), female from Pará, Bragança (MPEG). 81. Abdominal sternites and tergite 6 in ventral view. 82. Epiproct, cercus and hypoproct in apical view. 83. Spermatheca in lateral view. 84. Abdomen in posterior view. 85. Abdomen in dorsal view. 86. Abdomen in ventral view. Scale bars: 79, 83–84 = 2 mm; 80 = 0.5 mm; 81 = 0.1 mm; 82 = 1 mm. Abbreviations: CE = cercus; EP = epiproct; HP = hypoproct; ST = sternite; T = tergite." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1456147/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">84</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[983,1015,1508,1532]" captionStart="FIGURES 87–92" captionStartId="25.[151,264,1905,1928]" captionTargetBox="[173,1435,193,1885]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[151,1435,193,1885]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURES 87–92. Peckia (Peckia) lutzi (Lopes), female from Pará, Bragança (MPEG). 87. Abdominal sternites and tergite 6 in ventral view. 88. Epiproct, cercus and hypoproct in apical view. 89. Spermatheca in apical view. 90. Abdomen in posterior view. 91. Abdomen in dorsal view. 92. Abdomen in ventral view. Scale bars: 85, 88–90 = 2 mm; 86–87 = 0.5 mm. Abbreviations: CE = cercus; EP = epiproct; HP = hypoproct; ST = sternite; T = tergite." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1456149/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">90</figureCitation>
). In addition, these three species are found mainly along the coast. Females of 
<taxonomicName box="[629,755,1543,1568]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Pattonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gulo" subGenus="Peckia">
<emphasis box="[629,650,1545,1568]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[667,686,1545,1568]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[705,755,1543,1568]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">gulo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from females of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Aldrich" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[1192,1358,1543,1568]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Pattonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hillifera" subGenus="Peckia">
<emphasis box="[1192,1213,1545,1568]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1230,1249,1545,1568]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1268,1358,1543,1568]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">hillifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Pattonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lutzi" subGenus="Peckia">
<emphasis box="[1415,1437,1545,1568]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[160,179,1581,1604]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[199,248,1580,1605]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">lutzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the following features: T5 reddish with spots of silver microtrichosity and a row of thick spine-like setae near posterior margin; ST6 with only one pair of median robust setae; T6 with grooves on its surface (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 75–80" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1907,1930]" captionTargetBox="[176,1416,193,1882]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[168,1416,193,1890]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 75–80. Peckia (Peckia) gulo (Fabricius), female from Pará, Bragança (MPEG). 75. Abdominal sternites and tergites 5 and 6 in ventral view. 76. Epiproct, cercus and hypoproct in apical view. 77. Spermatheca in lateral view. 78. Abdomen in posterior view. 79. Abdomen in dorsal view. 80. Abdomen in ventral view. Scale bars: 73, 76–78 = 2 mm; 74–75 = 0.5 mm. Abbreviations: CE = cercus; EP = epiproct; HP = hypoproct; ST = sternite; T = tergite." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1456145/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Figs 75, 78</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[193,268,1652,1676]" captionStart="FIGURES 81–86" captionStartId="24.[151,264,1911,1934]" captionTargetBox="[176,1406,197,1883]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[173,1406,193,1888]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 81–86. Peckia (Peckia) hillifera (Aldrich), female from Pará, Bragança (MPEG). 81. Abdominal sternites and tergite 6 in ventral view. 82. Epiproct, cercus and hypoproct in apical view. 83. Spermatheca in lateral view. 84. Abdomen in posterior view. 85. Abdomen in dorsal view. 86. Abdomen in ventral view. Scale bars: 79, 83–84 = 2 mm; 80 = 0.5 mm; 81 = 0.1 mm; 82 = 1 mm. Abbreviations: CE = cercus; EP = epiproct; HP = hypoproct; ST = sternite; T = tergite." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1456147/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">81, 84</figureCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Aldrich" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[319,484,1652,1677]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Pattonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hillifera" subGenus="Peckia">
<emphasis box="[319,337,1653,1676]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[356,374,1653,1676]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[393,484,1652,1677]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">hillifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[539,662,1652,1677]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Pattonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lutzi" subGenus="Peckia">
<emphasis box="[539,558,1653,1676]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[577,595,1653,1676]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[614,662,1652,1677]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">lutzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
T5 is brownish-black with spots of silver microtrichosity and with a row of long, not spine-like setae near posterior margin; ST6 has more than one pair of robust setae near posterior margin, and T6 lacks grooves on its surface. In addition, 
<taxonomicName box="[786,910,1724,1749]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Pattonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gulo" subGenus="Peckia">
<emphasis box="[786,805,1725,1748]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[823,841,1725,1748]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[860,910,1724,1749]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">gulo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a large and robust species, reaching up to 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="20.0">20 mm</quantity>
in length, while 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Aldrich" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[383,547,1759,1784]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Pattonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hillifera" subGenus="Peckia">
<emphasis box="[383,402,1761,1784]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[420,439,1761,1784]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[457,547,1759,1784]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">hillifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[602,723,1759,1784]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Pattonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lutzi" subGenus="Peckia">
<emphasis box="[602,620,1761,1784]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[638,657,1761,1784]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">P.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[675,723,1759,1784]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">lutzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
reach about 
<quantity box="[867,949,1760,1784]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="17.0">17 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,895,2001]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
This species was collected only on oceanic beaches and in mangroves in the Brazilian Amazon, with traps baited with rotting organic matter (dead fish and crab, fermented banana and pineapple); it seems to be restricted to estuaries and marshy coastal habitats (
<bibRefCitation box="[585,799,1868,1893]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refId="ref18968" refString="Reeves, W. K., Pape, T. &amp; Adler, P. H. (2000) Biological notes on New World Sarcophagidae (Diptera). Studia Dipterologica, 7, 497 - 500." type="journal article">
Reeves 
<emphasis box="[675,733,1868,1893]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al.</emphasis>
2000
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[812,1129,1868,1892]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refId="ref17113" refString="Buenaventura, E. &amp; Pape, T. (2013) Revision of the New World genus Peckia Robineau-Desvoidy (Diptera: Sarcophagidae). Zootaxa, 3622 (1), 1 - 87. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3622.1.1" type="journal article">Buenaventura &amp; Pape 2013</bibRefCitation>
). Its larvae appear to breed only in dead crabs (
<bibRefCitation box="[373,587,1903,1928]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refId="ref18968" refString="Reeves, W. K., Pape, T. &amp; Adler, P. H. (2000) Biological notes on New World Sarcophagidae (Diptera). Studia Dipterologica, 7, 497 - 500." type="journal article">
Reeves 
<emphasis box="[463,520,1903,1928]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al.</emphasis>
2000
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation box="[599,849,1903,1928]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refId="ref18557" refString="Mendez, J. &amp; Pape, T. (2002) Biology and immature stages of Peckia gulo (Fabricius, 1805) (Diptera: Sarcophagidae). Studia Dipterologica, 9, 371 - 374." type="journal article">Méndez &amp; Pape 2002</bibRefCitation>
), which is consistent with some specimens obtained from a dead crab [
<emphasis box="[373,559,1940,1965]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Ucides cordatus</emphasis>
(Linnaeus)] collected by Dr. Rita Santos (College Bragança, Universidade Federal do 
<collectingRegion box="[277,328,1976,2000]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Pará</collectingRegion>
) in mangroves of the Brazilian Amazon.
</paragraph>
